(2549, 195, 'Record and show credits', 1, 102, 1, 1, '2012-01-06 03:16:38', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2012-01-11', NULL, 'Queued', NULL, NULL, 'There is are links on testsales.php that go to refund.php to add a refund to the database. refund.php has not been built yet. \r\n\r\n1. It needs to have 2 fields: Refund date and refund amount. The refund amount should default to the purchase price.\r\n2. Both fields are required.\r\n3. You should show the name and address of the purchaser, the confirmation number, the test purchased and the purchase date on the page for informational purposes (so that Joe can verify he is recording the refund for the correct transaction). You will have to get this from several different tables but you can use the query on testsales.php as an example because it pulls all of those fields. You just need to change the where clause to select just the transaction indicated by the sale id number.\r\n4. When saving the refund you will need to update the refundamt and refund date fields in the examsales table using the id that is passed to refund.php in the url.\r\n5. After doing the save return to testsales.php showing just the sale transaction edited. If you pass the sale id back to it as a _GET variable you can change the filter in testsales.php to show just that record instead of doing all of the searching that it does now.\r\n\r\nAsk me if you have any questions.'),
